        "comparison_note_TWk9M7": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "supreme series",
            "series_2_name": "x05z zhen series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>SUPREME SERIES vs X05Z ZHEN SERIES</h3><p>Supreme focuses on practicality and reliability with German 1.4116 steel at 57  HRC, offering a perfect balance of toughness and stain-resistance for everyday home or commercial use. Zhen series features original Japanese ZDP189 Composite Steel hardened to 65-67 HRC and paired with exclusive North America Desert Ironwood handles—delivering the absolute longest edge retention and a truly high-end, collector-grade aesthetic.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Steel Core:</strong> Japanese ZDP189 Composite Steel (Zhen) vs. German $1.4116$ Steel (Supreme)</li><li><strong>Hardness:</strong> Zhen is significantly harder ($65-67$ HRC) for professional, high-end performance</li><li><strong>Edge Retention:</strong> Zhen holds sharpness substantially longer (5 stars vs. 4 stars)</li><li><strong>Handle:</strong> Exclusive Desert Ironwood (Zhen) vs. reliable Red Wood (Supreme)</li></ul><p></p><p>→ Choose X05Z Zhen for peak edge performance, luxury materials, and a collector-grade appearance<br/><br/>→ Choose Supreme if budget, high toughness, and easy maintenance are priorities</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_BYrAqT": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "lan series",
            "series_2_name": "retro series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Retro Series vs Lan Series</h3><p>Retro offers a balanced package: 10Cr15CoMoV composite steel at 60 HRC, four-star performance across toughness, edge holding, stain resistance and sharpening, plus handsome red wood and buffalo horn handles at mid-range pricing. Lan steps up to 14Cr14MoVNb powder steel core hardened higher, wrapped in 73-layer Damascus with deep freeze treatment and olive wood handles — delivering significantly longer edge life and a more exclusive look, with slightly less toughness than Retro.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Steel upgrade:</strong> Powder steel core (Lan) vs standard 10Cr15CoMoV (Retro)</li><li><strong>Edge retention:</strong> Lan holds sharpness much longer (5 stars vs 4 stars)</li><li><strong>Hardness:</strong> 2 HRC difference for pro-grade performance</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Top-tier investment vs mid-range value</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Retro</strong> for everyday versatility and value</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_jthWXc": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "mo series",
            "series_2_name": "retro series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Retro Series vs Mo Series</h3><p>Retro and Mo both use 10Cr15CoMoV at 60 HRC, so edge retention, toughness, corrosion resistance, and sharpening feel are very similar. Retro has 3-layer composite construction with red wood and black buffalo horn handles, giving a stylish yet traditional look at mid-level pricing. Mo pushes further into premium territory with 67-layer Damascus, deep freeze treatment, and a burnt oak handle — it feels more luxurious in hand and on the cutting board.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Construction:</strong> 67-layer Damascus (Mo) vs 3-layer composite (Retro)</li><li><strong>Handle style:</strong> Burnt oak vs red wood with buffalo horn</li><li><strong>Visual appeal:</strong> Mo's Damascus pattern for premium aesthetic</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Mo positioned as more decorative, high-end finish</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Retro</strong> for great all-around performance and classic styling<br/><strong>→ Choose Mo</strong> for the same steel with more luxurious Damascus finish</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_KBT3jM": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "retro  series",
            "series_2_name": "lan series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Retro Series vs Lan Series</h3><p>Retro offers a balanced package: 10Cr15CoMoV composite steel at 60 HRC, four-star performance across toughness, edge holding, stain resistance and sharpening, plus handsome red wood and buffalo horn handles at mid-range pricing. Lan steps up to 14Cr14MoVNb powder steel core hardened higher, wrapped in 73-layer Damascus with deep freeze treatment and olive wood handles — delivering significantly longer edge life and a more exclusive look, with slightly less toughness than Retro.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Steel upgrade:</strong> Powder steel core (Lan) vs standard 10Cr15CoMoV (Retro)</li><li><strong>Edge retention:</strong> Lan holds sharpness much longer (5 stars vs 4 stars)</li><li><strong>Hardness:</strong> 2 HRC difference for pro-grade performance</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Top-tier investment vs mid-range value</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Retro</strong> for everyday versatility and value<br/><strong>→ Choose Lan</strong> for maximum performance and prestige at the top price point</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_i6JB6V": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "mo series",
            "series_2_name": "lan series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Mo Series vs Lan Series</h3><p>Mo features 67-layer Damascus with a 10Cr15CoMoV core at 60 HRC, giving very balanced performance and a striking burnt oak handle, positioned above Retro but below Lan in pricing. Lan raises hardness to 62 HRC with a 14Cr14MoVNb powder steel core and 73-layer Damascus, paired with olive wood and advanced heat treatment — delivering stronger edge retention and a more high-end feel while sacrificing a little toughness.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Steel core:</strong> Powder steel (Lan) vs 10Cr15CoMoV (Mo) for better edge holding</li><li><strong>Hardness:</strong> 2 HRC bump for professional hardness level</li><li><strong>Edge retention:</strong> Lan maintains sharpness longer between sharpening</li><li><strong>Handle wood:</strong> Olive wood vs burnt oak for different aesthetics</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Mo</strong> for a premium, forgiving all-rounder<br/><strong>→ Choose Lan</strong> for the flagship option with the most aggressive edge holding and luxury presentation</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_eRajL8": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "supreme series",
            "series_2_name": "lan series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Supreme Series vs Lan Series</h3><p>Supreme sits at the entry point with 1.4116 steel that is tough, rust-resistant and quick to touch up — ideal for users who want a forgiving knife. Lan is the flagship series, built with 73-layer Damascus and a 14Cr14MoVNb powder steel core hardened to 62 HRC with deep freeze treatment and an olive wood handle. It trades some toughness for extreme edge retention and a very high-end look and feel.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Edge retention:</strong> Lan delivers razor-sharp performance that lasts significantly longer</li><li><strong>Hardness:</strong> 5 HRC difference for professional-grade hardness</li><li><strong>Construction:</strong> 73-layer Damascus vs monosteel for premium aesthetics</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Top-tier investment vs entry-level value</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Supreme</strong> for simple, durable value<br/><strong>→ Choose Lan</strong> for premium, high-hardness blade that holds a razor edge and sits at the top of the range</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_JzWn3T": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "supreme series",
            "series_2_name": "mo series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Supreme Series vs Mo Series</h3><p>Supreme focuses on practicality with red wood handles and 1.4116 steel that is very tough, stain-resistant, and easy to live with for everyday home use. Mo series features 67-layer Damascus cladding over 10Cr15CoMoV at 60 HRC plus a burnt oak handle and deep freeze heat treatment, delivering stronger edge holding, more refined cutting feel, and a striking Damascus pattern.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Aesthetics:</strong> Mo's 67-layer Damascus vs Supreme's plain finish</li><li><strong>Edge holding:</strong> Mo maintains sharpness much longer</li><li><strong>Handle:</strong> Burnt oak vs red wood for different grip and style</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Supreme</strong> if budget and easy maintenance are priorities<br/><strong>→ Choose Mo</strong> for noticeable performance and aesthetic upgrade at upper mid-range pricing</p>"
          }
        },
        "comparison_note_AU6A6k": {
          "type": "comparison_note",
          "settings": {
            "series_1_name": "supreme series",
            "series_2_name": "retro series",
            "comparison_text": "<h3>Supreme Series vs Retro Series</h3><p>Supreme uses German 1.4116 stainless steel at 57 HRC — the softest and most forgiving option with excellent toughness, corrosion resistance, and easy sharpening. Retro upgrades to a 3-layer 10Cr15CoMoV composite at 60 HRC with red wood and black buffalo horn handles, delivering noticeably better edge retention and a more premium feel while staying tough and easy to maintain.</p><p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Edge retention:</strong> Retro holds sharpness significantly longer</li><li><strong>Handle upgrade:</strong> Buffalo horn accent vs plain red wood</li><li><strong>Price:</strong> Small step up for noticeable performance gain</li></ul><p><strong>→ Choose Supreme</strong> for the best value workhorse<br/><strong>→ Choose Retro</strong> for longer-lasting sharpness and premium materials without a big price jump</p>"
          }
